                       Plant Preservation    Plant Research


                                   [anarule.gif]


      The National Center for Genetic Resources Preservation (NCGRP) is a
      USDA, ARS facility located on the Colorado State University campus in
      Fort Collins, Colorado.  The mission of NCGRP is to preserve the base
      collection of the National Plant Germplasm System and to conduct
      research to develop new technologies for preservation of seed and other
      propagules of plant genetic resources.

      Throughout the world, plant genetic diversity is being eroded as
      farmers in centers of diversity switch to hybrids and improved
      varieties.  Loss of germplasm, especially landrace varieties, will
      result in the loss of genes for high yield, disease and insect
      resistance, improved nutrition, and many other useful traits.  NCGRP
      preserves this genetic diversity from all over the world.


